<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="f22b1280c58aa78f3707dd0860cf8538" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> The Top Ten non-Minion Shadow Cards<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.21)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9268'>Mike "mikefrench" French</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9268&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 2, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Here they are, the cards I see as the most important for a successful Shadow deck (once you&#39;ve chosen your Culture)...<br />
<br />
10. Blade Tip / Black Breath.  Two of the nastiest cards, seen in every Nazgul deck on the face of the earth.  Why?  Because they kick butt!  Conditions that you can get out of your hand even if you have no minions in your hand, and once you do get a nazgul, they consistenly kill companions.  expert deck always come with 4 athelas or sleep, caradhras specifically to combat these two cards.  combos: Ulaire Lemenya.  Slap a Black Breath on a companion and he&#39;s suddenly strength -2.  add the sword of minas morgul on lemmy to inflict some extra damage, then when you win the skirmish, give him a blade tip (or just use morgul blades if you mysteriously have problems winning skirmishes with your nazgul).  Watch out for stealth events; i&#39;ve always wanted to play a combo nazgul/sauron deck with trackers and Seeking it Always to cancel those pesky hobbit stealths.  imagine the look on the opponent&#39;s face when suddenly power 7 merry with sword has to fight ulaire lemenya with sword and take two wounds, a black breath and a blade tip. ouch.<br />
<br />
9. Return to its Master.  any card that can instantly win the game is a good card in my opinion.  This particular one is perhaps the hardest to pull off (except for Despair), but it&#39;s still viable.  Combo: shadow archery (Orc Bowmen?) against Isildur&#39;s Bane...someone decides to take the archery in the form of burdens on frodo, you wait until the end of the first skirmish, and kill frodo.  i like it.  another (somewhat idealistic) idea: Saruman&#39;s reach and Hate.  This would be tough, to make a somewhat balanced deck around nazgul, sauron, and with enough uruk-hai to make this combo work, but it would almost guarantee a win.<br />
<br />
8. Bitter Hatred. What is the biggest fellowship deck today?  directed archery via Aragorn&#39;s Bow and Legolas, Greenleaf.  My suggestion is to fight fire with fire.  Your opponent decides to exert Legolas too many times?  He will live to regret it when Legolas dies.  The Arwen and Aragorn fellowship big?  kill off Arwen.  only costs one twilight, requires no exertions, just hafta spot a moria archer.  cheap card, excellent gameplay potential.<br />
<br />
7. All Blades Perish. costs nothing, prevents a wound on your nazgul.  ARV with archery kills nazgul, All Blades Perish rescues them.  simple as that.<br />
<br />
6. Beauty is Fading. I once played a game against my brother&#39;s killer nazgul deck, and he only had one of this card at the time.  i started at the prancing pony, played aragorn, and moved to his site two, Weatherhills, giving him 11.  He played Ulaire Nelya for 5 and in the manuever phase, Beauty is Fading.  I had to read the card three times.  He discarded my only Aragorn.  Pissed the heck outta me.  Ever since, i have been in awe of this card.<br />
<br />
5. Goblin Armory.  The most versatile card in the game.  This card singlehandedly makes Moria the cheapest culture, and in my opinion, the best.  Last game i played was against an elven culture.  gimme 4 twilight, i played a scavenger for 3, got a weapon to add one, played two runners to add two more, two moria scouts for free, another scavenger (with They are Coming, #11 on my list) for 3, got a scimitar to add one, drew a scimitar, played it to add another, and finished off with a wallcrawler and a backstabber.  eight minions for 4 twilight, all because of Goblin Armory and goblin scimitars.  Plus, its not unique!  play 4!  add 4 when you play a weapon.  then discard one of them to prevent a wound.  makes up nice for low goblin vitality, and really pisses off opponents who are tryin to choke you with no twilight.  <br />
<br />
4. Worry.  the best card to play in a multiplayer tourney.  Plus its just irritating. combine with traitor&#39;s voice to slow down the fellowship big time to beat him to victory.  plus burden strategy can be big for isengard, via worry, uruk spies and saruman&#39;s reach.  plus with worry, you can count on your uruk&#39;s to win a few skirmishes.  =)<br />
<br />
3. Hate.  I love this card.  win some skirmishes with the band of the eye or orc scouting bands to wound companions.  next turn deploy some dudes and finish off the exhausted companions.  or, stop their directed archery in the manuever phase.  can&#39;t exert legolas to kill an orc if legolas is exhausted from two hates.  plus the card costs no twilight, which is really good, coming from the always-roaming never-cheap culture.  Or if you want originality, combine a sauron deck with nazgul.  inflict big bad wounds with fierce nazgul, follow up with hate the next manuever phase to kill companions.  beautiful card.<br />
<br />
2. The Irresistible Shadow.  i love strategy.  the game would be soo boring if it were only about power and vitality.  this card oozes strategy. (i should get good reviews just for using cool words like &quot;ooze&quot;.)  its free, its a condition, and it wins games.  like i said before, any card that can instantly win the game is a good card.  Sauron culture can deal out burdens like no other, and too many people bid too high and start the prancing pony, so five burdens really isnt that hard to get.  and with cards like Desperate Defense of the Ring and Desperate Measures and Band of the Eye, discarding is a powerful strategy.  Combine this with a fellowship deck that emphasizes making your opponent discard too, and you&#39;ve got a winner.<br />
<br />
1. Desperate Defense of the Ring.  Non-unique condition that plays for only one on any companion.  Once on the companion, havoc is wreaked.  Sure, the first few times they can add a burden, since they only have two, but after they see The Irresistible Shadow hit the table, they start to panic.  They hafta discard three cards.  What happens if you have two Desperate Defenses on two companions?  6 cards get discarded.  If they only have 4 cards, they hafta add a burden instead.  Or combine this with Desperate Measures.  They add a burden, you take it away and make em discard 5 cards.  FIVE cards!  This happens 2, 3 times, and suddenly your opponent&#39;s strategy gets shot in the foot.  again, a truly beautiful card.<br />
<br />
well, thanks for reading, i hope you enjoyed my favorite and most teched out shadow cards out there.  <br />
<br />
mike the mad maia <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=3244&view=1&PHPSESSID=f22b1280c58aa78f3707dd0860cf8538'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?PHPSESSID=f22b1280c58aa78f3707dd0860cf8538'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=f22b1280c58aa78f3707dd0860cf8538'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
